args: Rrrrrraaaaaaagh! Thaaat's it! I'm done!\nI AIN'T DOIN' NO MORE!
Enough with the cleaning!\nI wanna have some FUN!
A boy may have fun \nwhen his chores are all done.

Aw, I hate rhymes that tell me bad news...
C'moooon, Cleo! I mean, yeah, I get it,
dirt is the enemy or whatever, but it's
NEW YEAR'S!
Most people spend the end of the year\ncelebrating, but WE go nuts cleaning this\njoint from attic to cellar. What gives?!

We're all partied out from Dragonyule,
but instead of sleeping it off, I'm scrubbin'
grout. The holidays are s'posed to be
for relaxing, not THIS!
We clean precisely BECAUSE\nthe year is ending.
Yeah, that's always how we roll\nover in Hinomoto.
Of course. Who would not wish to begin\nthe new year with a fresh slate as well\nas a clean home?
Besides, cleaning is thought to welcome\nboth happiness and good fortune into\nyour home for the coming year.
Welcoming good fortune, hm? That's an\ninteresting way of thinking about it.
You didn't know, Cleo? I thought that's\nwhy you were joining in on the tradition.
No, I'd never heard of it. I just feel like\nthe Halidom deserves some respect and\nthanks after serving us for the year.
The New Year's decorations we put out\nafter cleaning also mean stuff.
Our culture's pretty deep when you get\nright down to it!
Okay, now I'm curious. Tell me more!
It is ever a joy to share our ways\nwith friends from abroad. But first...
You know, I think this every year, but\nbetween the decorations and the kimonos,\nyou guys really go all out!
Oh, speaking of, you said the decorations\nhad some kind of special meaning, yeah?
Well, what's with the stack of mochi\nwearing a fruit hat?

Those are known as kagami mochi.
It is a most auspicious food that
symbolizes a wish for a bountiful harvest
as we embark on the new year.
There is also meaning in the fact that\nthe mochi are stacked upon each other.
There are also prescriptions for where they\nare to be displayed, as well as what day\none should put them out.
All that just for rice cakes?
Oh, yes. We have rituals for all of our\ndecorations, including the kadomatsu\nbamboo ornaments and shimenawa ropes.
Wow, man. We're pretty close allies with\nyou guys and I had NO idea...
I would be happy to teach you more\nif you desire; part of my role here IS as\na cultural emissary, after all.
In that case, lay it on me! This stuff is all\nsuper rad, PLUS I get to learn more about\nall of you guys!
I am glad to hear it. In that case,\nlet me begin with the decorations...
After hearing all about Hinomotoan New Year's\nornamentation, Luca excitedly ran off...
Where do you suppose he went?
Yo, Ranzal! He went that way!
Is everyone here all right?!\nI heard a most terrifying racket.
Yeah, funny story! After you taught me all\nabout those ornaments, I got the urge to\ndo a little decorating myself.
I was walking through the forest, saw a big\nol' fiend, and thought, ＂Hey! I bet THAT guy\ncould use a little holiday festivity!＂
And this chaos is the result.
Whew! He's a slippery fella, but I finally\nwrangled him into that cage.
Thanks, man. I'll take it from here.
I can safely say it has never occurred to\nme to decorate a fiend. As I THOUGHT I\nexplained earlier, these ornaments are—
Oh, yeah! About that! I'd love to hear more\nabout all your guys' celebrations.
I mean, yeah, okay. Probably shouldn't\nhave tried to hang stuff on a fiend's teeth.\nBut next time will be WAY better.
Plus, Hinomoto's our buddy! I wanna get\nto know you all better.
Look, more than anything, I wanna have\nFUN this New Year's, so lay it on me!\nGimme Hinomotoan New Year's 101!
Very well. I'll shall spread the word.
Let's all have a lovely year-end together.
Woooo! This year, we're doin' it up\nfull-on Hinomoto style!
